{"cursor":"44206","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Roger Bacon honorific_suffix = Order of Friars Minor image = Roger-bacon-\n| statue.jpg caption = Statue of Roger Bacon in the Oxford University Museum\n| birth_date = c. 1214 birth_place = Ilchester, Somerset death_date = 1294 (aged\n| c. 80) death_place = Oxford Linda S. Noelker, Kenneth Rockwood, Richard\n| Sprott (ed.), [http://books.google.gr/books?id=VgQAqz_ABUgC&dq= The\n| Encyclopedia of Aging: A-K], Springer Publishing Company, 2006, p. 69.\n| other_names = Doctor Mirabilis occupation = Friar, scholar organization =\n| Order of Friars Minor nationality = English religion = Roman Catholic\n}}\n\n'Roger Bacon', O.F.M. (c. 1214â1294) (scholastic accolade Doctor Mirabilis,\nmeaning \"wonderful teacher\"), was an English philosopher and Franciscan friar\nwho placed considerable emphasis on the study of nature through empirical\nmethods. He is sometimes credited, mainly starting in the 19th century, as one\nof the earliest European advocates of the modern scientific method inspired by\nthe works of Aristotle and later Arabic works, such as the works of Muslim\nscientist Alhazen. However, more recent reevaluations\nemphasize that he was essentially a medieval thinker, with much of his\n\"experimental\" knowledge obtained from books, in the scholastic\ntradition. Glick, Thomas F.; Livesey, Steven John; Wallis, Faith: Medieval\nScience, Technology, and Medicine: An Encyclopedia, first edition, Routledge,\nSeptember 29, 2005, ISBN 978-0-415-96930-7, p. 71 A survey of the\nreception of Bacon's work over centuries found that it often reflects the\nconcerns and controversies central to the receivers.\n","linknr":868,"url":"Roger_Bacon","recorded":1363577381,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Roger_Bacon&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Roger_Bacon&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.w